Foot & mouth disease, suspected - Belgium 20010303.043
Date: 5 Mar 2001
From: Pig Disease Information Centre <pdic@btinternet.org>
Source: News agencies [edited

Belgian Federal Minister of Agriculture, Jaak Gabriels, said the first
results of blood tests on suspect animals are negative. Definitive results
are expected.Tuesday morning [2 Mar 2001.
The following measures are being taken in Belgium to prevent spreading of FMD:
1. Total ban on movement of all farm animals in the entire country. This
includes cattle, sheep, goat, deer, horses, rabbits and chickens.
2. Access to farms is forbidden for people and vehicles foreign to the farm.
3. All pigs are to be kept indoors.
4. All farms with even-toed ungulate animals must have disinfection
available for visitors.
5. Farm-pets have to be locked inside.
6. All horse shows and competitions are banned.
7. Only veterinarians and other necessary personnel are allowed on the
farm, after necessary precautions.
8. The wheels of each vehicle leaving a farm have to be disinfected.
9. Around the suspected farm in Diksmuide (West-Vlaanderen) a buffer zone
has been established.
This is bordered as follows:
From "Oostende" at the North sea, over the A10/E40, then south over the
A17, then A22/E17 to the French Border.
10. In the buffer zone the following measures are in force:
Access to each farm with even-toed ungulate animals has to be blocked with
a chain and a sign saying "access forbidden."
Transport of any meat from even-hoofed animals, milk, and other products
that might transmit the virus is forbidden.
Collecting of milk is permitted only under specific conditions.
--
Pig Disease Information Centre
<pdic@btinternet.com>
